{{one source|date=November 2016}} {{italic title}} {{Jmyth infobox}} {{nihongo|'''''Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things'''''|ÊÄ™Ë´á|Kaidan|also ''Kwaidan'' (archaic)}}, often shortened to '''''Kwaidan''''' ("[[ghost story]]"), is a book by [[Lafcadio Hearn]] that features several [[kaidan|Japanese ghost stories]] and a brief non-fiction study on insects.<ref>[[Brian Stableford]], "Kwaidan", in [[Frank N. Magill]], ed. ''Survey of Modern Fantasy Literature'', Vol 2. Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Salem Press, Inc., 1983, {{ISBN|0-89356-450-8}} (pp. 859-860).</ref> It was later used as the basis for a movie called ''[[Kwaidan (film)|Kwaidan]]'' by [[Masaki Kobayashi]] in 1964.
==Stories== Hearn declares in his introduction to the first edition of the book, which he wrote on January 20, 1904, shortly before his death, that most of these stories were translated from old Japanese texts. He also states that one of the stories ‚Äì ''[[Yuki-onna]]'' ‚Äì was told to him by a farmer in [[Musashi Province]], and his was apparently the first record of it, both by his own account and according to the research of modern folklorists. ''Riki-Baka'' is based on a personal experience of Hearn's. While he does not declare it in his introduction, ''Hi-Mawari'' ‚Äì among the final narratives in the volume ‚Äì seems to be a recollection of an experience in his childhood (it is, setting itself apart from almost all the others, written in the [[first-person narrative|first person]] and set in rural [[Wales]]).
*''[[H≈çichi the Earless|The Story of Mimi-nashi H≈çichi]]'' *''Oshidori'' *''The Story of O-Tei'' *''Ubazakura'' *''Diplomacy'' *''Of a Mirror and a Bell'' *''[[Jikininki]]'' *''[[Noppera-b≈ç#The Mujina of the Akasaka Road|Mujina]]'' *''[[Rokurokubi]]'' (description of ''[[Rokurokubi (folktale)|folktale]]'') *''A Dead Secret'' *''[[Yuki-Onna]] *''The Story of Aoyagi'' *''Jiu-Roku-Zakura'' *''[[The Dream of Akinosuke]]'' *''Riki-Baka'' *''Hi-Mawari'' *''[[Mount Penglai|H≈çrai]]''
==Insect studies== In the last half of the book, Hearn listens collected Chinese/Japanese superstitions and his own personal thoughts on various members of the insect world. *''[[Butterflies]]'': [[Personification]] of the human [[soul]]. *''[[Mosquitoes]]'': [[Karmic]] [[reincarnation]] of jealous or greedy people in the form of ''Jiki-ketsu-gaki'' or "blood-drinking [[Hungry ghost#In Japan|pretas]]". *''[[Ants]]'': Mankind's superior in terms of [[chastity]], [[ethics]], [[social structure]], [[longevity]] and [[evolution]].
