'''Romantic realism''' is [[art]] which combines elements of both [[romanticism]] and [[realism (arts)|realism]]. The terms "romanticism" and "realism" have been used in varied ways,<ref>{{cite book | title=Joseph Conrad: His Romantic-Realism |last=Stauffer |first=Ruth M. |publisher=Kessinger Publishing |location= |year=2006 |origyear=1922 |isbn=1-4286-5840-8 |page=13 |quote=It would be wearisome even to enumerate the books and essays that have been written in all languages to define these two terms.}}</ref> and are sometimes seen as opposed to one another.<ref>{{cite book | title=Romanticism |last=Abercrombie |first=Lascelles |authorlink=Lascelles Abercrombie |publisher=Barnes and Noble |location=New York |year=1963 |origyear=1926 |page=61 |quote=For there is an element directly opposed to romanticism : it is realism. The true antithesis, then, is between romanticism and realism.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=The Study of English Literature |last1=Cowardin Jr. |first1=Samuel Pendleton |last2=More |first2=Paul Elmer |authorlink2=Paul Elmer More |publisher=Henry Holt and Company |location=New York |year=1939 |page=138 |quote=And it follows as a corollary that realism is, on the whole, the opposite of romanticism; for, as we have seen, romanticism is usually bound up with idealism.}}</ref>

==In literature and art==
The term has long standing in literary criticism.<ref>{{cite book |title=Realism in Modern Literature |last=Becker |first=George J. |publisher=Frederick Ungar |location=New York |year=1980 |isbn=0-8044-2031-9 |page=102 |quote=Essentially exhibiting a paradox, this term has come into being among critics and historians in an attempt to characterize writing of the nineteenth century which is incompletely realistic.}}</ref> For example, [[Joseph Conrad]]'s relationship to romantic realism is analyzed in Ruth M. Stauffer's 1922 book ''Joseph Conrad: His Romantic Realism''. [[Liam O'Flaherty]]'s relationship to romantic realism is discussed in P.F. Sheeran's book ''The Novels of Liam O'Flaherty: A Study in Romantic Realism''. [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky]] is described as a romantic realist in Donald Fanger's book, ''Dostoevsky and Romantic Realism: A Study of Dostoevsky in Relation to Balzac, Dickens, and Gogol''. Historian [[Jacques Barzun]] argued that romanticism was falsely opposed to realism<ref>{{cite book |title=Classic, Romantic, and Modern |last=Barzun |first=Jacques |authorlink=Jacques Barzun|publisher=University of Chicago Press |location= |edition=revised second |year=1975 |origyear=1943 |isbn=0-226-03852-1|page=58 |quote=I now want to argue against this postponement of the realistic label and to suggest that on the evidence just set forth, romanticism ''is'' realism.}}</ref> and declared that "...the romantic realist does not blink his weakness, but exerts his power."<ref>{{cite book |title=Classic, Romantic, and Modern |last=Barzun |first=Jacques |authorlink=Jacques Barzun|publisher=University of Chicago Press |location= |edition=revised second |year=1975 |origyear=1943 |isbn=0-226-03852-1|page=77}}</ref>

The term also has long standing in art criticism.<ref>{{cite book |title=American Art of Our Century |last=Goodrich |first=Lloyd |last2=Baur |first2=John I. H. |publisher=Frederick A. Praegar |location=New York |year=1961 |page=121 |quote=Romantic realism, long a powerful movement in American painting, has unquestionably waned since 1940. It has never disappeared, and some of its finest examples are recent ones, but it is significant that most of the painting reproduced here are by artist now dead or well past their middle years}}</ref> Art scholar John Baur described it as "a form of realism modified to express a romantic attitude or meaning".<ref>{{cite book |title=American Art of Our Century |last=Goodrich |first=Lloyd |last2=Baur |first2=John I. H. |publisher=Frederick A. Praegar |location=New York |year=1961 |page=121}}</ref> According to [[Theodor W. Adorno]], the term "romantic realism" was used by [[Joseph Goebbels]] to define the official doctrine of the [[Nazi art|art produced in Nazi Germany]], although this usage did not achieve wide currency.<ref>{{cite book |first=Carl |last=Dahlhaus |others=trans. by Mary Whittall |title=Realism in Nineteenth-century Music |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=New York |year=1985 |isbn=0-521-26115-5 |page=58 |quote=The vague universality of the term 'romantic realism', which helped it to become a catchphrase, led eventually to political misuse as well. ... T.W. Adorno, paradoxically enough, cited [[Joseph Goebbels]], who had spoken of 'romantic realism', evidently in order to signify his approval ... }}</ref>

Novelist and philosopher [[Ayn Rand]] described herself as a romantic realist,<ref>{{cite book |title=[[The Romantic Manifesto]]: A Philosophy Of Literature |last=Rand |first=Ayn |authorlink=Ayn Rand|publisher=Signet |location=New York |year=1971 |isbn=0-451-14916-5 |edition=revised |page=167}}</ref> and many followers of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]] who work in the arts apply this term to themselves. As part of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)#Aesthetics: metaphysical value-judgments|her aesthetics]], Rand defined romantic realism as a portrayal of life "as it could be and should be."<ref>{{cite book |ref=harv |title=[[Letters of Ayn Rand]] |last=Rand |first=Ayn |authorlink=Ayn Rand |editor-first=Michael S |editor-last=Berliner |location=New York |publisher=Dutton |year=1995 |isbn=0-525-93946-6 |page=243}}</ref> She wrote: "The method of romantic realism is to make life more beautiful and interesting than it actually is, yet give it all the reality, and even a more convincing reality than that of our everyday existence."<ref>{{cite book |ref=harv |title=[[Letters of Ayn Rand]] |last=Rand |first=Ayn |authorlink=Ayn Rand |editor-first=Michael S |editor-last=Berliner |location=New York |publisher=Dutton |year=1995 |isbn=0-525-93946-6 |pages=242‚Äì243}}</ref>

== In music ==
"Realism" in music is often associated with the use of music for the depiction of objects, whether they be real (as in [[Bed≈ôich Smetana]]'s "Peasant Wedding" of ''[[Die Moldau]]'') or mythological (as in [[Richard Wagner]]'s [[Ring cycle]]). [[Musicologist]] [[Richard Taruskin]] discusses what he calls the "black romanticism" of [[Niccol√≤ Paganini]] and [[Franz Liszt]], i.e., the development and use of musical techniques that can be used to depict or suggest "grotesque" creatures or objects, such as the "laugh of the [[devil]]", to create a "frightening atmosphere."<ref>{{cite book |ref=harv | last=Taruskin |first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Taruskin |title=The Oxford History of Western Music. Volume 3: The Nineteenth Century|location= New York |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-19-516979-9 |page=255 and 264}}</ref> Thus, Taruskin's "black romanticism" is a form of "romantic realism" deployed by nineteenth-century virtuosi with the intent of invoking fear or "the [[Sublime (philosophy)|sublime]]."

